{"id": "8851", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=8851", "title": "December 14", "text": "December 14\n\nBULLET::::- 557 – Constantinople is severely damaged by an earthquake.\nBULLET::::- 835 – Sweet Dew Incident: Emperor Wenzong of the Tang dynasty conspires to kill the powerful eunuchs of the Tang court, but the plot is foiled.\nBULLET::::- 1287 – St. Lucia's flood: The Zuiderzee sea wall in the Netherlands collapses, killing over 50,000 people.\nBULLET::::- 1542 – Princess Mary Stuart becomes Queen of Scots at the age of one week on the death of her father, James V of Scotland.\nBULLET::::- 1751 – The Theresian Military Academy is founded in Wiener Neustadt, Austria.\nBULLET::::- 1780 – Founding Father Alexander Hamilton marries Elizabeth Schuyler Hamilton at the Schuyler Mansion in Albany, New York\nBULLET::::- 1782 – The Montgolfier brothers first test fly an unmanned hot air balloon in France; it floats nearly .\nBULLET::::- 1812 – The French invasion of Russia comes to an end as the remnants of the Grande Armée are expelled from Russia.\nBULLET::::- 1814 – War of 1812: The Royal Navy seizes control of Lake Borgne, Louisiana.\nBULLET::::- 1819 – Alabama becomes the 22nd U.S. state.\nBULLET::::- 1836 – The Toledo War unofficially ends.\nBULLET::::- 1896 – The Glasgow Underground Railway is opened by the Glasgow District Subway Company.\nBULLET::::- 1900 – Quantum mechanics: Max Planck presents a theoretical derivation of his black-body radiation law.\nBULLET::::- 1902 – The Commercial Pacific Cable Company lays the first Pacific telegraph cable, from San Francisco to Honolulu.\nBULLET::::- 1903 – The Wright brothers make their first attempt to fly with the \"Wright Flyer\" at Kitty Hawk, North Carolina.\nBULLET::::- 1907 – The , the largest ever ship without a heat engine, runs aground and founders near the Hellweather's Reef within the Isles of Scilly in a gale. The pilot and 15 seamen die.\nBULLET::::- 1909 – New South Wales Premier Charles Wade signs the Seat of Government Surrender Act 1909, formally completing the transfer of State land to the Commonwealth to create the Australian Capital Territory.\nBULLET::::- 1911 – Roald Amundsen's team, comprising himself, Olav Bjaaland, Helmer Hanssen, Sverre Hassel, and Oscar Wisting, becomes the first to reach the South Pole.\nBULLET::::- 1913 – , the fourth and last ship, launches, eventually becoming one of the Japanese workhorses during World War I and World War II.\nBULLET::::- 1914 – Lisandro de la Torre and others found the Democratic Progressive Party (\"Partido Demócrata Progresista\", PDP) at the Hotel Savoy, Buenos Aires, Argentina.\nBULLET::::- 1918 – Friedrich Karl von Hessen, a German prince elected by the Parliament of Finland to become King Väinö I, renounces the Finnish throne.\nBULLET::::- 1918 – Portuguese President Sidónio Pais is assassinated.\nBULLET::::- 1918 – The 1918 United Kingdom general election occurs, the first where women were permitted to vote.\nBULLET::::- 1939 – Winter War: The Soviet Union is expelled from the League of Nations for invading Finland.\nBULLET::::- 1940 – Plutonium (specifically Pu-238) is first isolated at Berkeley, California.\nBULLET::::- 1941 – World War II: Japan signs a treaty of alliance with Thailand.\nBULLET::::- 1948 – Thomas T. Goldsmith Jr. and Estle Ray Mann are granted a patent for their cathode-ray tube amusement device, the earliest known interactive electronic game.\nBULLET::::- 1955 – Albania, Austria, Bulgaria, Cambodia, Ceylon, Finland, Hungary, Ireland, Italy, Jordan, Laos, Libya, Nepal, Portugal, Romania and Spain join the United Nations through United Nations Security Council Resolution 109.\nBULLET::::- 1958 – The 3rd Soviet Antarctic Expedition becomes the first to reach the southern pole of inaccessibility.\nBULLET::::- 1960 – Convention against Discrimination in Education of UNESCO is adopted.\nBULLET::::- 1962 – NASA's \"Mariner 2\" becomes the first spacecraft to fly by Venus.\nBULLET::::- 1963 – The dam containing the Baldwin Hills Reservoir bursts, killing five people and damaging hundreds of homes in Los Angeles, California.\nBULLET::::- 1964 – American Civil Rights Movement: \"Heart of Atlanta Motel v. United States\": The Supreme Court of the United States rules that Congress can use the Constitution's Commerce Clause to fight discrimination.\nBULLET::::- 1971 – Bangladesh Liberation War: Over 200 of East Pakistans intellectuals are executed by the Pakistan Army and their local allies. (The date is commemorated in Bangladesh as Martyred Intellectuals Day.)\nBULLET::::- 1972 – Apollo program: Eugene Cernan is the last person to walk on the moon, after he and Harrison Schmitt complete the third and final extravehicular activity (EVA) of the \"Apollo 17\" mission.\nBULLET::::- 1981 – Arab–Israeli conflict: Israel's Knesset ratifies the \"Golan Heights Law\", extending Israeli law to the occupied Golan Heights.\nBULLET::::- 1985 – Wilma Mankiller takes office as the first woman elected to serve as Principal Chief of the Cherokee Nation.\nBULLET::::- 1992 – War in Abkhazia: Siege of Tkvarcheli: A helicopter carrying evacuees from Tkvarcheli is shot down, resulting in at least 52 deaths, including 25 children. The incident catalyses more concerted Russian military intervention on behalf of Abkhazia.\nBULLET::::- 1994 – Construction begins on the Three Gorges Dam on the Yangtze river.\nBULLET::::- 1995 – Yugoslav Wars: The Dayton Agreement is signed in Paris by the leaders of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, Croatia, and Bosnia and Herzegovina.\nBULLET::::- 1998 – Yugoslav Wars: The Yugoslav Army ambushes a group of Kosovo Liberation Army fighters attempting to smuggle weapons from Albania into Kosovo, killing 36.\nBULLET::::- 1999 – Torrential rains cause flash floods in Vargas, Venezuela, resulting in tens of thousands of deaths, the destruction of thousands of homes, and the complete collapse of the state's infrastructure.\nBULLET::::- 2003 – Pakistani President Pervez Musharraf narrowly escapes an assassination attempt.\nBULLET::::- 2004 – The Millau Viaduct, the tallest bridge in the world, is formally inaugurated near Millau, France.\nBULLET::::- 2008 – Muntadhar al-Zaidi throws his shoes at then-U.S. President George W. Bush during a press conference in Baghdad, Iraq.\nBULLET::::- 2012 – Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting: Twenty-eight people, including the gunman, are killed in Sandy Hook, Connecticut.\nBULLET::::- 2013 – A reported coup attempt in South Sudan leads to continued fighting and hundreds of casualties.\nBULLET::::- 2017 – The Walt Disney Company announces that it would acquire 21st Century Fox, including the 20th Century Fox movie studio, for $52.4 billion.\n\nBULLET::::- 1009 – Go-Suzaku, emperor of Japan (d. 1045)\nBULLET::::- 1332 – Frederick III, German nobleman (d. 1381)\nBULLET::::- 1546 – Tycho Brahe, Danish astronomer and chemist (d. 1601)\nBULLET::::- 1599 – Charles Berkeley, 2nd Viscount Fitzhardinge, English politician (d. 1668)\nBULLET::::- 1607 – János Kemény, Hungarian prince (d. 1662)\nBULLET::::- 1625 – Barthélemy d'Herbelot, French orientalist and academic (d. 1695)\nBULLET::::- 1631 – Anne Conway, English philosopher and author (d. 1679)\nBULLET::::- 1640 – Aphra Behn, English playwright and author (d. 1689)\nBULLET::::- 1678 – Daniel Neal, English historian and author (d. 1743)\nBULLET::::- 1720 – Justus Möser, German jurist and theorist (d. 1794)\nBULLET::::- 1730 – Capel Bond, English organist and composer (d. 1790)\nBULLET::::- 1738 – Jan Antonín Koželuh, Czech composer and educator (d. 1814)\nBULLET::::- 1775 – Philander Chase, American bishop and educator, founded Kenyon College (d. 1852)\nBULLET::::- 1775 – Thomas Cochrane, 10th Earl of Dundonald, Scottish admiral and politician (d. 1860)\nBULLET::::- 1777 – Du Pre Alexander, 2nd Earl of Caledon, Irish politician, Lord Lieutenant of Tyrone (d. 1839)\nBULLET::::- 1784 – Princess Maria Antonia of Naples and Sicily (d. 1806)\nBULLET::::- 1789 – Maria Szymanowska, Polish composer and pianist (d. 1831)\nBULLET::::- 1791 – Charles Wolfe, Irish priest and poet (d. 1823)\nBULLET::::- 1794 – Erastus Corning, American businessman and politician (d. 1872)\nBULLET::::- 1816 – Abraham Hochmuth, Hungarian rabbi and educator (d. 1889)\nBULLET::::- 1824 – Pierre Puvis de Chavannes, French painter and illustrator (d. 1898)\nBULLET::::- 1832 – Daniel H. Reynolds, American general, lawyer, and politician (d. 1902)\nBULLET::::- 1851 – Mary Tappan Wright, American novelist and short story writer (d. 1916)\nBULLET::::- 1852 – Daniel De Leon, Curaçaoan-American journalist and politician (d. 1914)\nBULLET::::- 1853 – Errico Malatesta, Italian activist and theorist (d. 1932)\nBULLET::::- 1856 – Louis Marshall, American lawyer and activist (d. 1929)\nBULLET::::- 1866 – Roger Fry, English painter and critic (d. 1934)\nBULLET::::- 1870 – Karl Renner, Austrian lawyer and politician, 4th President of Austria (d. 1950)\nBULLET::::- 1881 – Katherine MacDonald, American actress and producer (d. 1956)\nBULLET::::- 1883 – Manolis Kalomiris, Greek pianist and composer (d. 1962)\nBULLET::::- 1883 – Morihei Ueshiba, Japanese martial artist, developed aikido (d. 1969)\nBULLET::::- 1884 – Jane Cowl, American actress and playwright (d. 1950)\nBULLET::::- 1887 – Xul Solar, Argentinian painter and sculptor (d. 1963)\nBULLET::::- 1894 – Alexander Nelke, Estonian-American painter and carpenter (d. 1974)\nBULLET::::- 1895 – George VI of the United Kingdom (d. 1952)\nBULLET::::- 1895 – Paul Éluard, French poet and author (d. 1952)\nBULLET::::- 1896 – Jimmy Doolittle, American general and pilot, Medal of Honor recipient (d. 1993)\nBULLET::::- 1897 – Kurt Schuschnigg, Italian-Austrian lawyer and politician, 15th Federal Chancellor of Austria (d. 1977)\nBULLET::::- 1897 – Margaret Chase Smith, American educator and politician (d. 1995)\nBULLET::::- 1899 – DeFord Bailey, American Hall of Fame country and blues musician (d. 1982)\nBULLET::::- 1901 – Henri Cochet, French tennis player (d. 1987)\nBULLET::::- 1901 – Paul of Greece (d. 1964)\nBULLET::::- 1902 – Frances Bavier, American actress (d. 1989)\nBULLET::::- 1902 – Herbert Feigl, Austrian philosopher from the Vienna Circle (d. 1988)\nBULLET::::- 1903 – Walter Rangeley, English sprinter (d. 1982)\nBULLET::::- 1904 – Virginia Coffey, American civil rights activist (d. 2003)\nBULLET::::- 1908 – Morey Amsterdam, American actor, singer, and screenwriter (d. 1996)\nBULLET::::- 1908 – Claude Davey, Welsh rugby player (d. 2001)\nBULLET::::- 1908 – Mária Szepes, Hungarian journalist, author, and screenwriter (d. 2007)\nBULLET::::- 1909 – Edward Lawrie Tatum, American geneticist and academic, Nobel Prize laureate (d. 1975)\nBULLET::::- 1911 – Spike Jones, American singer and bandleader (d. 1965)\nBULLET::::- 1911 – Hans von Ohain, German-American physicist and engineer (d. 1998)\nBULLET::::- 1911 – Jerzy Iwanow-Szajnowicz, Greek-Polish swimmer and water polo player (d. 1943)\nBULLET::::- 1914 – Karl Carstens, German lieutenant and politician, 5th President of the Federal Republic of Germany (d. 1992)\nBULLET::::- 1914 – Rosalyn Tureck, American pianist and harpsichord player (d. 2003)\nBULLET::::- 1915 – Dan Dailey, American dancer and actor (d. 1978)\nBULLET::::- 1916 – Shirley Jackson, American novelist and short story writer (d. 1965)\nBULLET::::- 1917 – C.-H. Hermansson, Swedish author and politician (d. 2016)\nBULLET::::- 1917 – Elyse Knox, American actress and fashion designer (d. 2012)\nBULLET::::- 1917 – June Taylor, American dancer and choreographer (d. 2004)\nBULLET::::- 1918 – James T. Aubrey, American broadcaster (d. 1994)\nBULLET::::- 1918 – Radu Beligan, Romanian actor and director (d. 2016)\nBULLET::::- 1918 – B. K. S. Iyengar, Indian yoga instructor and author, founded Iyengar Yoga (d. 2014)\nBULLET::::- 1920 – Clark Terry, American trumpet player, composer, and educator (d. 2015)\nBULLET::::- 1922 – Nikolay Basov, Russian p