{"id": "8852", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=8852", "title": "December 13", "text": "December 13\n\nBULLET::::- 1294 – Saint Celestine V resigns the papacy after only five months to return to his previous life as an ascetic hermit.\nBULLET::::- 1545 – The Council of Trent begins.\nBULLET::::- 1577 – Sir Francis Drake sets sail from Plymouth, England, on his round-the-world voyage.\nBULLET::::- 1636 – The Massachusetts Bay Colony organizes three militia regiments to defend the colony against the Pequot Indians. This organization is recognized today as the founding of the National Guard of the United States.\nBULLET::::- 1642 – Abel Tasman is the first recorded European to sight New Zealand.\nBULLET::::- 1643 – English Civil War: The Battle of Alton takes place in Hampshire.\nBULLET::::- 1758 – The English transport ship \"Duke William\" sinks in the North Atlantic, killing over 360 people.\nBULLET::::- 1769 – Dartmouth College is founded by the Reverend Eleazar Wheelock, with a royal charter from King George III, on land donated by Royal governor John Wentworth.\nBULLET::::- 1818 – Cyril VI of Constantinople resigns from his position as Ecumenical Patriarch.\nBULLET::::- 1862 – American Civil War: At the Battle of Fredericksburg, Confederate General Robert E. Lee defeats Union Major General Ambrose Burnside.\nBULLET::::- 1867 – A Fenian bomb explodes in Clerkenwell, London, killing six.\nBULLET::::- 1928 – George Gershwin's \"An American in Paris\" is first performed.\nBULLET::::- 1937 – Second Sino-Japanese War: Battle of Nanking: The city of Nanjing, defended by the National Revolutionary Army under the command of General Tang Shengzhi, falls to the Japanese. This is followed by the Nanking Massacre, in which Japanese troops rape and slaughter hundreds of thousands of civilians.\nBULLET::::- 1938 – The Holocaust: The Neuengamme concentration camp opens in the Bergedorf district of Hamburg, Germany.\nBULLET::::- 1939 – World War II: Battle of the River Plate: Captain Hans Langsdorff of the German Deutschland-class cruiser (pocket battleship) \"Admiral Graf Spee\" engages with Royal Navy cruisers , and .\nBULLET::::- 1943 – World War II: The Massacre of Kalavryta by German occupying forces in Greece.\nBULLET::::- 1949 – The Knesset votes to move the capital of Israel to Jerusalem.\nBULLET::::- 1959 – Archbishop Makarios III becomes the first President of Cyprus.\nBULLET::::- 1960 – While Emperor Haile Selassie of Ethiopia visits Brazil, his Imperial Bodyguard seizes the capital and proclaims him deposed and his son, Crown Prince Asfa Wossen, Emperor.\nBULLET::::- 1962 – NASA launches \"Relay 1\", the first active repeater communications satellite in orbit.\nBULLET::::- 1967 – Constantine II of Greece attempts an unsuccessful counter-coup against the Regime of the Colonels.\nBULLET::::- 1968 – Brazilian President Artur da Costa e Silva issues AI-5 (Institutional Act No. 5), enabling government by decree and suspending habeas corpus.\nBULLET::::- 1972 – Apollo program: Eugene Cernan and Harrison Schmitt begin the third and final extra-vehicular activity (EVA) or \"Moonwalk\" of \"Apollo 17\". To date they are the last humans to set foot on the Moon.\nBULLET::::- 1974 – Malta becomes a republic within the Commonwealth of Nations.\nBULLET::::- 1977 – Air Indiana Flight 216 crashes near Evansville Regional Airport, killing 29, including the University of Evansville basketball team, support staff, and boosters of the team.\nBULLET::::- 1981 – General Wojciech Jaruzelski declares martial law in Poland, largely due to the actions by \"Solidarity\".\nBULLET::::- 1982 – The 6.0 North Yemen earthquake shakes southwestern Yemen with a maximum Mercalli intensity of VIII (\"Severe\"), killing 2,800, and injuring 1,500.\nBULLET::::- 1988 – PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat gives a speech at a UN General Assembly meeting in Geneva, Switzerland, after United States authorities refused to grant him a visa to visit UN headquarters in New York.\nBULLET::::- 1989 – The Troubles: Attack on Derryard checkpoint: The Provisional Irish Republican Army launches an attack on a British Army temporary vehicle checkpoint near Rosslea, Northern Ireland. Two British soldiers are killed and two others are wounded.\nBULLET::::- 2001 – Sansad Bhavan, the building housing the Indian Parliament, is attacked by terrorists. Twelve people are killed, including the terrorists.\nBULLET::::- 2002 – European Union enlargement: The EU announces that Cyprus, the Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Malta, Poland, Slovakia, and Slovenia will become members on May 1, 2004.\nBULLET::::- 2003 – Iraq War: Operation Red Dawn: Former Iraqi President Saddam Hussein is captured near his home town of Tikrit.\nBULLET::::- 2007 – The Treaty of Lisbon is signed by members states of the European Union.\nBULLET::::- 2011 – A murder–suicide in Liège, Belgium, kills six and wounds 125 people at a Christmas market.\nBULLET::::- 2018 – A high-speed train crashes in Ankara, Turkey, killing at least nine people and injuring 84.\n\nBULLET::::- 1272 – King Frederick III of Sicily (d. 1337)\nBULLET::::- 1363 – Jean Gerson, chancellor of the University of Paris (d. 1429)\nBULLET::::- 1476 – Lucy Brocadelli, Dominican tertiary and stigmatic (d. 1544)\nBULLET::::- 1484 – Paul Speratus, German Lutheran (d. 1551)\nBULLET::::- 1491 – Martín de Azpilcueta, Spanish theologian and economist (d. 1586)\nBULLET::::- 1499 – Justus Menius, German Lutheran pastor (d. 1558)\nBULLET::::- 1521 – Pope Sixtus V (d. 1590)\nBULLET::::- 1533 – Eric XIV of Sweden (d. 1577)\nBULLET::::- 1553 – Henry IV of France (d. 1610)\nBULLET::::- 1560 – Maximilien de Béthune, Duke of Sully, 2nd Prime Minister of France (d. 1641)\nBULLET::::- 1585 – William Drummond of Hawthornden, Scottish poet (d. 1649)\nBULLET::::- 1640 – Robert Plot, English chemist and academic (d. 1696)\nBULLET::::- 1662 – Francesco Bianchini, Italian astronomer and philosopher (d. 1729)\nBULLET::::- 1678 – Yongzheng Emperor of China (d. 1735)\nBULLET::::- 1720 – Carlo Gozzi, Italian playwright (d. 1804)\nBULLET::::- 1724 – Franz Aepinus, German astronomer and philosopher (d. 1802)\nBULLET::::- 1769 – James Scarlett Abinger, English judge (d. 1844)\nBULLET::::- 1780 – Johann Wolfgang Döbereiner, German chemist, invented the Döbereiner's lamp (d. 1849)\nBULLET::::- 1784 – Archduke Louis of Austria (d. 1864)\nBULLET::::- 1797 – Heinrich Heine, German journalist, poet, and critic (d. 1856)\nBULLET::::- 1804 – Joseph Howe, Canadian journalist and politician, 5th Premier of Nova Scotia (d. 1873)\nBULLET::::- 1814 – Ana Néri, Brazilian nurse and philanthropist (d. 1880)\nBULLET::::- 1816 – Werner von Siemens, German engineer and businessman, founded Siemens (d. 1892)\nBULLET::::- 1818 – Mary Todd Lincoln, 16th First Lady of the United States (d. 1882)\nBULLET::::- 1830 – Mathilde Fibiger, Danish feminist, novelist and telegraphist (d. 1892)\nBULLET::::- 1836 – Franz von Lenbach, German painter and academic (d. 1904)\nBULLET::::- 1854 – Herman Bavinck, Dutch philosopher, theologian, and academic (d. 1921)\nBULLET::::- 1856 – Svetozar Boroević, Croatian-Austrian field marshal (d. 1920)\nBULLET::::- 1860 – Lucien Guitry, French actor (d. 1925)\nBULLET::::- 1864 – Emil Seidel, American woodcarver and politician, 36th Mayor of Milwaukee (d. 1947)\nBULLET::::- 1867 – Kristian Birkeland, Norwegian physicist and author (d. 1917)\nBULLET::::- 1870 – Edward LeSaint, American actor and director (d. 1940)\nBULLET::::- 1871 – Emily Carr, Canadian painter and author (d. 1945)\nBULLET::::- 1874 – Josef Lhévinne, Russian pianist and educator (d. 1944)\nBULLET::::- 1882 – Jane Edna Hunter, African-American social worker (d. 1971)\nBULLET::::- 1883 – Belle da Costa Greene, American librarian (d. 1950)\nBULLET::::- 1884 – Aimilios Veakis, Greek actor, director, and playwright (d. 1951)\nBULLET::::- 1885 – Annie Dale Biddle Andrews, American mathematician (d. 1940)\nBULLET::::- 1887 – G